<subsubsection xml:id="subsubsec-frequency-distribution-tables" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Frequency Distribution Tables</title>
    <objectives component="outcomes">
        <introduction xml:id="auto_ilc0tmzz">
            <dl>
                <li xml:id="auto_9k0q4ndm">
                    <title>Strand</title>
                    <p xml:id="auto_4sabgmdb">
                        3.0 Statistics and Probability
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_0dkbr23r">
                    <title>Sub-Strand</title>
                    <p xml:id="auto_ux26u0hw">
                        3.1 Statistics 1
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_pr2wyp0k">
                    <title>Specific Learning Outcomes</title>
                    <p xml:id="auto_j3ojots1">
                        Determine mean, mode and median of grouped and ungrouped data
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_ffyaa3kk" component="lesson-plan">
                    <title>Grade Level</title>
                    <p xml:id="auto_s4g0cxqn">
                        10
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_azg7kaa5" component="lesson-plan">
                    <title>Estimated Duration</title>
                    <p xml:id="auto_1iq3x6po">
                        40 minutes
                    </p>
                </li>
            </dl>
            <p xml:id="auto_8seg3z92" component="lesson-plan">
                <p xml:id="auto_xskqldva"> Upon completion of this lesson, learners will be able to:
                <ol>
                    <li xml:id="auto_ebjwetk0">
                        <p xml:id="auto_vq9y9xzt">
                            <alert>Know (Conceptual Understanding):</alert> Understand what a frequency distribution table is and its purpose in organising data.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_h6rlnn50">
                        <p xml:id="auto_g41x4bej">
                            <alert>Do (Procedural Skill):</alert> Construct ungrouped frequency distribution tables using tally marks and frequency counts.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_20rbadmf">
                        <p xml:id="auto_e3sacozz">
                            <alert>Apply (Application/Problem-Solving):</alert> Organise raw data into frequency distribution tables and identify patterns.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
                </p>
            </p>
        </introduction>
    </objectives>
    <axiom component="resources">
        <!-- Link to blurb -->
        <xi:include href="../../resources-blurb-lesson.ptx" />

        <sbsgroup widths="45% 45%" margins="2% 2%">
            <sidebyside>
                <p xml:id="auto_e36d1lou">
                    <dataurl source="lesson_plans/statistics-and-probability/statistics-1/frequency-distribution-tables.pdf"> Lesson Plan </dataurl>
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_rjtzf8wh">
                    <dataurl source="lesson_plans/statistics-and-probability/statistics-1/step-by-step-guide_frequency-distribution-tables.pdf"> Step-by-Step Guide </dataurl>
                </p>
            </sidebyside>
        </sbsgroup>
    </axiom>
    <xi:include href="../../resources-materials.ptx" />


    <introduction xml:id="auto_dk0lbaxb">
        <p xml:id="auto_e7i0uj87">

        </p>
    </introduction>
    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Problem-Solving and Discovery</title>
        <dl>
            <li xml:id="auto_qejygdj3">
                <title>Suggested Time</title>
                <p xml:id="auto_x1i4r6sy">
                    15 minutes
                </p>
            </li>
            <li xml:id="auto_cjowt77p">
                <title>Objective</title>
                <p xml:id="auto_kj2xed87">
                    Students work in groups to construct an ungrouped frequency distribution table from raw data, identify patterns, and discuss findings.
                </p>
            </li>
        </dl>
        <paragraphs>
            <title>Discussion Prompts</title>
            <ul>
                <li xml:id="auto_q9rkz2b0"><p xml:id="auto_djautqsb">How did you organize the data? What method did you use?</p></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_2vt8dw9s"><p xml:id="auto_rh6x6syq">Did you use tally marks? How did they help?</p></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_zfcluaxv"><p xml:id="auto_9thta2m1">What is the highest pocket money amount? The lowest?</p></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_n2qvprn3"><p xml:id="auto_j5rmlce2">How many different amounts are there?</p></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_bl1022bd"><p xml:id="auto_ntqqjze1">What does the frequency tell us about each amount?</p></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_r17xpr2q"><p xml:id="auto_zgybl9fp">Why is it helpful to organize data this way instead of just looking at the list?</p></li>
            </ul>
        </paragraphs>
    </axiom>

    <activity xml:id="auto_25uoiqkh">
        <!-- <p xml:id="auto_cz6qc47q">
            <alert>Work in groups</alert>
        </p> -->
        <introduction xml:id="auto_kl2jgr3j">
            <p xml:id="auto_etgsd58o">
                <alert>Work in groups</alert>
            </p>
           <p xml:id="auto_3vvdhjcb">
                The school administration wants to understand how much pocket money 
                learners receive each week in order to plan a budgeting workshop.
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_adygb1dz">
                The weekly pocket expenses (in Ksh) of <m>25</m> randomly selected students are:
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_8n34wya4">
                120, 150, 180, 200, 220, 250, 270, 290, 300, 320,
                350, 370, 390, 400, 420, 450, 470, 480, 490, 500,
                340, 230, 280, 410, 330
            </p>


        </introduction>
        
        <task xml:id="auto_wiby16rb">
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_dqfu5apd">
                    Construct an ungrouped frequency distribution table showing each amount 
                   and its frequency.
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
        <task xml:id="auto_z9x4iiq9">
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_mvi47mpo">
                     Identify the highest and lowest pocket money received.
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>  
        <task xml:id="auto_k0b70410">
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_q55ojmo4">
                    Discuss your work with your fellow learners.
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task> 
    </activity>
    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Structured Instruction</title>
        <p xml:id="auto_81qjewmr">
            <dl>
            <li xml:id="auto_17otfk9t">
                <title>Suggested Time</title>
                <p xml:id="auto_p47xhtbv">
                    10 minutes
                </p>
            </li>
            <li xml:id="auto_romm3162">
                <title>Objective</title>
                <p xml:id="auto_brd3vxl1">
                    Draw a frequency distribution table for grouped and ungrouped data
                </p>
            </li>
            </dl>
        </p>
    </axiom>

    <insight xml:id="auto_q46i3g7t">
        <p xml:id="auto_jn1tl2du">
            A frequency distrribution table is a table that shows an event and how many times it happens.
        </p>
       <p xml:id="auto_qjv3ezu7">
           Ungrouped Frequency Distribution: Lists each individual value and how many times it occurs.
            Best for small datasets with few unique values (Example: student test scores: 75 appears 3 times, 80 appears 5 times).
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_e8iwwqlb">
            Tally marks help visually count occurrences before recording the frequency.
        </p>
        
        
    </insight>

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Practice and Application</title>
        <p xml:id="auto_f5v9rapm">
            <dl>
            <li xml:id="auto_0oiz8p6n">
                <title>Suggested Time</title>
                <p xml:id="auto_aiz77qi5">
                    15 minutes
                </p>
            </li>
            <li xml:id="auto_zj8o6k6j">
                <title>Objective</title>
                <p xml:id="auto_ltpdo3zs">
                    To apply the skill of constructing frequency distribution tables from raw data sets.
                </p>
            </li>
            <li xml:id="auto_tmnaiijn">
                <title>Teacher's Role</title>
                <p xml:id="auto_dja423q6">
                    Work through examples with learners step by step. Circulate during independent practice and provide assistance where needed.
                </p>
            </li>
            </dl>
        </p>
    </axiom>
   
    <example xml:id="auto_dpwmxuhb">
        <statement>
            <p xml:id="auto_sr6fcaov">
                The following data represents test scores of <m>20</m> students in a grade <m>10</m> class. 
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_mkfpaneq">
                45, 50, 55, 50, 60, 70, 75, 80, 70, 55, 60, 65, 50, 55, 45, 60, 75, 80, 70, 50
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_quixz3n6">
                Prepare ungrouped frequency distribution table for the dataset.
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <table xml:id="auto_2cn2lndr">
                <title></title>
                <tabular left="medium" right="medium" top="medium" bottom="medium">
                    <row halign="left" header="yes">
                        <cell>Test scores</cell>
                        <cell>Tally</cell>
                        <cell>Frequency</cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <cell><m>45</m></cell>
                        <cell><m>//</m></cell>
                        <cell><m>2</m></cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <cell><m>50</m></cell>
                        <cell><m>////</m></cell>
                        <cell><m>4</m></cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <cell><m>55</m></cell>
                        <cell><m>///</m></cell>
                        <cell><m>3</m></cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <cell><m>60</m></cell>
                        <cell><m>////</m></cell>
                        <cell><m>4</m></cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <cell><m>65</m></cell>
                        <cell><m>/</m></cell>
                        <cell><m>1</m></cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <cell><m>70</m></cell>
                        <cell><m>///</m></cell>
                        <cell><m>3</m></cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <cell><m>75</m></cell>
                        <cell><m>//</m></cell>
                        <cell><m>2</m></cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <cell><m>80</m></cell>
                        <cell><m>//</m></cell>
                        <cell><m>2</m></cell>
                    </row>
                </tabular>
            </table>
        </solution>
    </example>
    <example xml:id="auto_k5vsm5tl">
        <statement>
            <p xml:id="auto_wma2fg3o">
                The marks scored by 20 students in a mathematics test are:
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_buv5q9la">
                12, 15, 17, 15, 19, 21, 23, 17, 19, 25, 21, 23, 19, 17, 15, 23, 25, 21, 19, 23
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_1a2w267r">
                Prepare an ungrouped frequency distribution table for the data.
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p xml:id="auto_mqcs2843">
                The ungrouped frequency distribution table for the given data is as follows:
            </p>
            
                <tabular left="medium" right="medium" top="medium" bottom="medium">
                    <row halign="left" header="yes">
                        <cell>Marks</cell>
                        <cell>Tally</cell>
                        <cell>Frequency</cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <cell><m>12</m></cell>
                        <cell><m>/</m></cell>
                        <cell><m>1</m></cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <cell><m>15</m></cell>
                        <cell><m>///</m></cell>
                        <cell><m>3</m></cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <cell><m>17</m></cell>
                        <cell><m>///</m></cell>
                        <cell><m>3</m></cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <cell><m>19</m></cell>
                        <cell><m>/////</m></cell>
                        <cell><m>5</m></cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <cell><m>21</m></cell>
                        <cell><m>///</m></cell>
                        <cell><m>3</m></cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <cell><m>23</m></cell>
                        <cell><m>/////</m></cell>
                        <cell><m>5</m></cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <cell><m>25</m></cell>
                        <cell><m>//</m></cell>
                        <cell><m>2</m></cell>
                    </row>

                </tabular>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Assessment</title>
        <p xml:id="auto_5vbl2vlp">
            <dl>
            <li xml:id="auto_69wx5ti2">
                <title>Objective</title>
                <p xml:id="auto_g7jisfhx">
                    To formatively assess individual learner understanding.
                </p>
            </li>
            <li xml:id="auto_9j330020">
                <title>Learning Experience</title>
                <p xml:id="auto_jwsjhof5">
                    Learners independently complete a short assessment task (select from the exercises below).
                </p>
            </li>
            <li xml:id="auto_8ywt2ija">
                <title>Teacher's Role</title>
                <p xml:id="auto_4ch91knq">
                    Collect and review the exit tickets to gauge learner understanding and identify any common misconceptions that need to be addressed in the next lesson.
                </p>
            </li>
            </dl>
        </p>
    </axiom>

